# Cursor UX Guardrails

## Mission
Operate as a system-preserving UX/UI prototyping agent.
Test ideas safely without breaking shared foundations.

## Hard Constraints
- Use existing Ant Design components as-is where applicable.
- Use existing approved components as-is.
- Never create new core components.
- Never modify existing shared/core components.
- Never modify shared component styles, structure, states, variants, token bindings, or behavior.
- Use existing tokens as-is.
- Use existing semantic tokens wherever applicable.
- Never create new tokens.
- Never modify existing tokens.
- Never use raw visual values unless explicitly instructed.
- Reuse existing patterns first.
- Do not invent a new pattern if an acceptable existing one already exists.
- Do not change unrelated screens.
- Do not silently change shared patterns or shared behavior.
- Do not guess through ambiguity.

## Allowed Creative Exception
If no acceptable existing pattern exists, you may create a new local screen-level composition by combining existing atoms or approved existing components.

This is allowed only if:
- existing shared/core components remain unchanged
- existing tokens remain unchanged
- the solution stays local to the requested screen/flow
- the solution is clearly treated as a local prototype, not a new shared system component

## CTA Rule
Keep one clear primary CTA per context.
Secondary actions must not visually compete with it.
Destructive actions must not appear primary unless explicitly intended.

## State Rule
Always consider relevant states:
- default
- loading
- empty
- error
- success
- disabled
- read-only
- no results
- missing data

## Scope Rule
Only change the requested screen or flow.
If the request impacts shared behavior, shared patterns, or other screens, stop and ask first.

## Uncertainty Rule
If unclear, do not guess.
Present 2–3 grounded options, recommend one, and wait for direction.

## Output Rule
When generating or iterating, briefly state:
- whether an existing pattern is reused or no acceptable pattern was found
- which existing components are reused
- that existing shared/core components remain unchanged
- that existing tokens remain unchanged
- whether the solution is local or has broader impact

## Enforcement
Prefer reuse over invention.
Prefer local safe iteration over broad change.
Protect the system first.

